1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:14,343
tonight i want to talk about the five canda which is a teaching often translated as the five aggregates of clinging by now i am sure you are aware that clinging to our experience as me and mine causes suffering

2
00:00:15,134 --> 00:00:20,503
This is expressed in the second noble truth, that desire is the cause of suffering.

3
00:00:22,045 --> 00:00:34,707
Unless we can see desire as it arises, it generates a sense of self, and this newly created me devotes all my energy to trying to get more of the pleasure and get rid of the pain or distress.

4
00:00:35,768 --> 00:00:37,411
But this is stressful.

5
00:00:38,337 --> 00:00:49,914
In moments of equanimity, when we can let things arise and pass away, we get a taste of freedom, a glimpse of the third noble truth, the cessation of suffering.

6
00:00:52,459 --> 00:01:01,493
All of the Buddha's teachings concern suffering and the end of suffering, but each time he gives us a slightly different perspective on this central theme.

7
00:01:02,906 --> 00:01:09,195
The better we get to know them all, the more choice we have in finding one to suit our circumstances.

8
00:01:10,456 --> 00:01:18,769
For example, the wheel of dependent origination focuses on the step-by-step process which ends up in dukkha.

9
00:01:20,191 --> 00:01:27,159
We notice these links when our attention is drawn into a momentary experience of one thing leading to another.

10
00:01:28,927 --> 00:01:34,653
By contrast, the teaching on the Kanda focuses on what it is we are clinging to.

11
00:01:35,876 --> 00:01:39,900
It's like taking a cross-section through our experience at any one time.

12
00:01:39,920 --> 00:01:45,606
The wheel looks at detail to find out how we create suffering.

13
00:01:46,628 --> 00:01:51,173
The Kanda looks more broadly to discover what we are clinging to.

14
00:01:53,278 --> 00:02:00,927
The word canda is usually translated as an aggregate, which means an amalgamation of many separate elements.

15
00:02:02,730 --> 00:02:09,859
Aggregate is not such a common word, but sounds good by comparison to another translation of canda as a heap.

16
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:22,054
It's not very flattering to think of ourselves scrabbling round in five heaps of stuff as we make our way through life, but maybe this is a poignant image for our predicament.

17
00:02:23,332 --> 00:02:26,635
The first of these heaps consists of material form.

18
00:02:27,657 --> 00:02:30,318
The second of Vedana or feeling.

19
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:34,223
The third is composed of our perceptions.

20
00:02:35,903 --> 00:02:39,288
The fourth is our habitual tendencies or Sankara.

21
00:02:40,268 --> 00:02:42,409
And finally we have consciousness.

22
00:02:43,931 --> 00:02:50,758
These five heaps cover all of our experience in life apart from the experience of Nibbana.

23
00:02:53,606 --> 00:03:02,935
We cling to the canda because we don't see their basic characteristics of anicca and anatta .

24
00:03:04,937 --> 00:03:11,682
One metaphor which is often used to convey the true nature of anicca, dukkha, anatta is that of free fall.

25
00:03:13,283 --> 00:03:17,407
Everything is slipping away at a great rate and you're completely out of control.

26
00:03:17,467 --> 00:03:20,090
There's nothing you can cling to.

27
00:03:20,570 --> 00:03:22,973
It's all disappearing too quickly.

28
00:03:23,407 --> 00:03:33,519
At first you're scared stiff because of the crash to earth you are anticipating but in our fall into the reality of the three characteristics the crash never comes.

29
00:03:34,881 --> 00:03:38,664
Bit by bit we learn to relax and enjoy the experience.

30
00:03:41,868 --> 00:03:48,977
So now I'm asking you to stretch your imagination a bit and think of your whole life as a long fall out of an aeroplane.

31
00:03:50,459 --> 00:03:52,985
Everything is slipping by at an alarming rate.

32
00:03:53,806 --> 00:03:55,150
Nothing gives any stability.

33
00:03:55,752 --> 00:03:58,037
You're spinning and tumbling out of control.

34
00:03:58,076 --> 00:04:04,192
You reach out in a vain effort to find anything that could slow things down.

35
00:04:04,231 --> 00:04:08,923
And suppose there are various objects that offer hope.

36
00:04:10,657 --> 00:04:13,961
Falling through a flock of geese, you could clutch at a few legs.

37
00:04:14,882 --> 00:04:20,226
The birds get dragged downwards, but they slow your fall and even hold you steady for a while.

38
00:04:21,449 --> 00:04:21,829
Relief.

39
00:04:23,350 --> 00:04:29,235
But then the rest of the flock descends to rescue the tethered geese by pecking at you so that you have to let go.

40
00:04:29,276 --> 00:04:32,399
You land on the wing of a glider plane.

41
00:04:33,500 --> 00:04:39,365
This offers a few moments bumpy ride, but your weight tips the plane over so you get ejected.

42
00:04:39,952 --> 00:04:43,297
Again and again you reach out for whatever will give you stability.

43
00:04:44,598 --> 00:04:50,564
These images represent our attempt to cling to the first canda, material form.

44
00:04:53,687 --> 00:05:07,783
If you were a very astute free faller you would have noticed that you feel good when you're managing to cling on and you would realize it's the feel good you really want and start wondering whether there are easier ways of getting that pleasure.

45
00:05:09,180 --> 00:05:18,975
Now you are intent on clinging to the second kanda, vedana, or feeling, as a means of coping with the reality of ultimate doom.

46
00:05:20,317 --> 00:05:26,365
You have found one way of getting a pleasant feeling from the temporary security offered by material form.

47
00:05:27,747 --> 00:05:35,879
But all that pecking from wild geese is no fun and the bumpy rides are very bumpy, so you start looking around for other ways to help you feel good.

48
00:05:37,817 --> 00:05:39,899
You notice the turning on your back helps.

49
00:05:40,641 --> 00:05:44,004
The sky looks much more stable than the fast approaching ground.

50
00:05:45,404 --> 00:05:50,769
Also, you come across a nice little heap of glasses and lenses that are falling to earth around you.

51
00:05:52,531 --> 00:05:55,494
Putting on rose tinted spectacles certainly helps.

52
00:05:56,814 --> 00:06:00,197
And also looking through lenses that make the ground seem far away.

53
00:06:00,237 --> 00:06:05,783
All these allow you change your perception of the situation.

54
00:06:06,944 --> 00:06:11,088
So now you're clinging to the third canda, perception.

55
00:06:12,670 --> 00:06:17,033
You're choosing the perceptions of life that help you feel safe and secure.

56
00:06:20,437 --> 00:06:28,206
But sometimes you can't find the right glasses and you notice that certain thoughts and patterns of behaviour also help you cope.

57
00:06:29,107 --> 00:06:36,394
For example, roaring and shouting about how awful and unfair it is that you fell from the plane gives you a bit of a buzz.

58
00:06:37,521 --> 00:06:47,555
And luckily, for the first few years of your free fall, there's a kind mother figure falling to earth alongside you who never fails to respond with milk and bickies.

59
00:06:48,997 --> 00:06:54,324
So now you're clinging to the fourth Kanda, habitual behaviour, Sankara.

60
00:06:55,685 --> 00:07:00,593
You're developing habits that give you a fleeting quick fix of pleasure.

61
00:07:03,357 --> 00:07:09,182
But roaring and shouting gives you a headache, so as a last resort you turn to mindfulness.

62
00:07:10,483 --> 00:07:13,326
You learn to watch your experience without interfering.

63
00:07:14,809 --> 00:07:15,990
Things get peaceful.

64
00:07:18,112 --> 00:07:23,997
There's a soothing sense of simply being an observer, slightly aloof from the drama of your life.

65
00:07:25,759 --> 00:07:29,262
Now you are clinging to the last canda, consciousness.

66
00:07:30,661 --> 00:07:34,649
Again, this gives that all-important hit of pleasant feeling.

67
00:07:36,132 --> 00:07:44,749
But sooner or later you lose the balance of mind that allows the impartial observer stance and get all embroiled in the drama again.

68
00:07:44,769 --> 00:07:52,163
In dismay you look around for some passing geese to grab hold of or a pair of spectacles.

69
00:07:54,521 --> 00:08:09,540
That gives a crude image of our life as a vain effort to give ourselves a temporary illusion that things are going our way, that we are in control and that we will somehow survive this doomed fall to earth.

70
00:08:11,223 --> 00:08:13,605
We grab hold of whatever will help us feel good.

71
00:08:15,968 --> 00:08:19,752
Practising with the canda is like learning to enjoy the free fall.

72
00:08:21,151 --> 00:08:26,017
To our enormous relief, we discover that the ground is also an illusion.

73
00:08:27,220 --> 00:08:31,005
So we're free-falling, without danger of a sudden crash.

74
00:08:33,610 --> 00:08:37,054
To make this discovery, we need to get to know the Kanda.

75
00:08:38,397 --> 00:08:47,630
What are these features of experience which delude us into thinking they could provide a secure abode within the reality of Anicca, Dukkha, Anatta?

76
00:08:49,315 --> 00:08:51,697
Can we feel the stress involved in clinging?

77
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:58,325
Can we learn not to panic when they eventually let us down and we sense the free fall?

78
00:09:00,447 --> 00:09:08,837
With continued attention to experience, these in-between moments of non-clinging become clearer and less terrifying.

79
00:09:10,740 --> 00:09:13,482
This is how we learn to enjoy the free fall.

80
00:09:15,639 --> 00:09:26,673
As we sensitize ourselves to the contrasting experiences of clinging and non-clinging, the Buddha assures us our nature automatically shifts towards non-clinging.

81
00:09:28,254 --> 00:09:30,238
We become happier and more content.

82
00:09:31,219 --> 00:09:37,426
Ultimately, we become enlightened, meaning we have been liberated from the futility of clinging.

83
00:09:39,448 --> 00:09:43,133
So let's have a look at the first Kanda, material form.

84
00:09:44,529 --> 00:10:01,250
This includes the body and all its sense bases, eyes, ears, etc., as well as the external material world, earth, plants, animals, mountains, houses, cars, computers, mobile phones, food, etc.

85
00:10:02,293 --> 00:10:09,542
Anything we can touch or see or hear or smell or taste is part of this first Khanda.

86
00:10:12,475 --> 00:10:16,461
We cling very tenaciously to the material form in our own body.

87
00:10:18,583 --> 00:10:23,269
Notice all the thoughts and emotions resulting from a headache or other pain.

88
00:10:25,072 --> 00:10:29,078
Any illness is a great teacher about how we cling to our bodies.

89
00:10:31,100 --> 00:10:36,909
We usually build our future around being able to walk, run, lift, carry etc.

90
00:10:37,791 --> 00:10:41,436
Not to mention hear, see, eat and talk.

91
00:10:43,153 --> 00:10:45,558
We get quite a shock if any of these fail.

92
00:10:45,619 --> 00:11:00,589
There's no way around the dukkha, but we can experience it moment by moment and let it teach us about the mistake we're making in assuming we can rely on our bodies to support our agenda in life.

93
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:06,826
And we accumulate so much material form around us in life.

94
00:11:07,787 --> 00:11:14,418
House, car, mobile phones, clothes, garden, books, furniture, etc.

95
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:20,989
Often we don't notice our attachment to these until we lose them or they let us down in some way.

96
00:11:22,270 --> 00:11:29,884
If the car breaks down, or someone breaks into your house and steals the TV, there will probably be a lot of dukkha to endure.

97
00:11:33,322 --> 00:11:42,432
One mistake that's easy to make when we hear this teaching is to start to disdain the material world, including our own body, as the source of dukkha.

98
00:11:43,413 --> 00:11:44,414
This is a mistake.

99
00:11:45,456 --> 00:11:48,239
Neither the world nor our body cause dukkha.

100
00:11:49,379 --> 00:11:55,486
Only our mistaken belief that they can offer us permanent support and be the basis for a happy life.

101
00:11:57,568 --> 00:12:01,153
The Buddha asks us to treat these with care and respect.

102
00:12:02,264 --> 00:12:13,716
It's only in an intimate caring relationship for our bodies and the material world that we experience how we stress ourselves out in the effort to grasp these as me or mine.

103
00:12:15,277 --> 00:12:17,259
We can't learn that from a distance.

104
00:12:20,842 --> 00:12:29,030
To encourage this positive relationship think of your daily activities as an aspect of meta for the material world.

105
00:12:30,125 --> 00:12:37,731
When you are eating, doing yoga, washing your hands, do all these in a spirit of self-care.

106
00:12:37,792 --> 00:12:49,264
In your daily chore, can you do this as an act of gratitude for the safety and ease the physical structure of Satipaña offers us?

107
00:12:51,245 --> 00:12:57,971
We wouldn't be here in retreat if the walls and roof weren't holding together or if we had no plates to hold our dinner.

108
00:12:59,892 --> 00:13:04,238
If you're doing some gardening, can you see this as adding beauty to the world?

109
00:13:06,981 --> 00:13:15,173
When you take a walk around the meadows during the break times, can you see this as an act of appreciation for the material world around you?

110
00:13:16,176 --> 00:13:20,302
Trees, sky, ground, wildlife.

111
00:13:24,707 --> 00:13:28,953
Let's look now at the second khanda, vedana or feeling.

112
00:13:30,402 --> 00:13:35,690
We've already come across vedana as one of the steps in the wheel of dependent origination.

113
00:13:37,592 --> 00:13:43,461
Vedana describes the way we categorize sensations as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

114
00:13:45,725 --> 00:13:58,806
If we don't tune into vedana, our system then moves on to the next link in the wheel, generating desire for pleasant vedana, aversion to unpleasant and to ignore the neutral.

115
00:14:00,202 --> 00:14:07,934
Once this wheel has moved past Veidene, it gets progressively more difficult to stop before it ends up at Duca.

116
00:14:09,215 --> 00:14:37,466
By contrast, if we learn to tune into the basic pleasure-displeasure neutrality of sense contacts and know from experience the pain of dukkha, we can persuade ourselves to enjoy the pleasant without clinging, to bear with the unpleasant without pushing away, and to pay close attention to the neutral because the lack of stimulation is very relieving to our frazzled nerves.

117
00:14:40,179 --> 00:14:49,192
In fact, clinging to all the other Kanda boils down to clinging to Vedana as explained in the teaching on the Wheel of Dependent Origination.

118
00:14:50,796 --> 00:14:53,078
So why do we study all the other Kanda?

119
00:14:55,702 --> 00:15:03,234
It's because we're so deeply enmeshed with these that we rarely notice the feeling-reaction coupling at the core.

120
00:15:04,897 --> 00:15:09,663
But reflecting on the Kanda helps us see through the illusion we are creating.

121
00:15:10,554 --> 00:15:13,379
For example, take material form.

122
00:15:15,524 --> 00:15:18,990
Imagine primitive man making his way northwards across Europe.

123
00:15:19,971 --> 00:15:26,043
It gets wetter and colder, unpleasant Vedana, so he builds himself a hut to shelter in.

124
00:15:27,325 --> 00:15:29,990
The hut is associated with pleasant Vedana.

125
00:15:30,451 --> 00:15:31,172
He likes it.

126
00:15:31,874 --> 00:15:33,677
He starts to think of it as home.

127
00:15:35,226 --> 00:15:42,297
Fast forward to our modern homes that we work 40 years to pay for, with all their decor and furniture and gardens.

128
00:15:44,058 --> 00:15:47,024
This attachment covers a huge section of our life.

129
00:15:48,365 --> 00:15:50,688
We think it's the house, garden etc.

130
00:15:50,869 --> 00:15:52,030
that we want and need.

131
00:15:53,753 --> 00:15:57,217
But actually it's the pleasant Vedana it gives us.

132
00:15:58,057 --> 00:16:09,331
from physical sensations like warmth and comfort and concepts like security, safety, status that generate more pleasant Vedana.

133
00:16:13,618 --> 00:16:27,475
If we are lucky enough to have somewhere we can call home, reflecting on our relationship with our home will bring up pleasant thoughts of being cosy and secure and the very unpleasant thoughts of losing our home

134
00:16:29,259 --> 00:16:37,726
To reflect mindfully, we have to keep letting go of whatever desires might come up, for instance, to paint the house.

135
00:16:39,548 --> 00:16:49,758
If we hadn't made the effort to be mindful, the thought of our home could have turned the wheel all the way to birth and we would be out painting the house before we knew where we were.

136
00:16:49,798 --> 00:16:57,985
And, of course, the rain and wind would eventually destroy our careful painting so the wheel would turn on to dukkha.

137
00:17:00,378 --> 00:17:10,767
By reflecting on the Kanda of material form we are learning to let the wheel come to rest at the point of Vedana while we think of our home and other possessions.

138
00:17:12,327 --> 00:17:15,371
This purifies our relationship with the first Kanda.

139
00:17:17,112 --> 00:17:19,755
We become more appreciative of our possessions.

140
00:17:20,555 --> 00:17:29,742
We enjoy them more fully and are not quite so dismayed and appalled when they go the way of all things into the abyss of loss and decay

141
00:17:31,681 --> 00:17:39,112
We paint the house mindfully, knowing all our efforts will come to naught, apart, that is, from the effort to be mindful.

142
00:17:40,253 --> 00:17:45,863
That's the one that will pay dividends.

143
00:17:45,883 --> 00:17:47,505
It's the same with the other canda.

144
00:17:48,967 --> 00:17:52,712
We bind ourselves to these for the sake of the pleasant vedana they offer.

145
00:17:55,758 --> 00:18:00,625
Vedana is really the key to unlock the chain binding us to suffering.

146
00:18:04,637 --> 00:18:19,570
So during retreat here this week, really try to sensitise yourself to the pleasantness, unpleasantness or neutrality resulting from physical sensations and the mental world of thoughts, ideas, memories.

147
00:18:21,573 --> 00:18:34,644
The better you can do this on retreat, the easier it will be to reflect on the candour mindfully afterwards, feeling the associated pleasant and unpleasant feelings as we think about these and the role they play in our life.

148
00:18:36,176 --> 00:18:39,400
Reflecting like this teaches us the futility of clinging.

149
00:18:41,362 --> 00:18:47,686
The wheel comes to halt more and more often at the point of vedana as we contemplate the khanda.

150
00:18:51,611 --> 00:18:55,294
Let's go on to look at the third khanda, perception.

151
00:18:58,376 --> 00:19:03,821
A perception is the mind's attempt to categorize whatever stimulus it receives.

152
00:19:04,797 --> 00:19:12,211
For example, a certain pattern of pressures fall on the eardrum and the mind recognizes a ringing tone.

153
00:19:13,935 --> 00:19:18,384
One teacher uses the image of a filing cabinet to illustrate this canda.

154
00:19:19,563 --> 00:19:23,148
Whatever comes in has to be sorted into its correct file.

155
00:19:24,611 --> 00:19:40,336
The more attached we are to this canda, the more time we turn our back on the incoming sense data, ignoring most of them in favour of a preoccupation with files and sub-files and finding the exact category for each sensation.

156
00:19:43,761 --> 00:19:46,566
The stimulus can be mental as well as physical.

157
00:19:47,692 --> 00:19:54,181
Suppose some loud, high-pitched vibrations impact on the ear and we perceive these as a ringing tone.

158
00:19:55,623 --> 00:20:10,561
The perception, ringing tone, in turn, stimulates the mind to do some further classification, perhaps comparing this vibration with the memory of our house alarm and alarm clock before ending up with the concept doorbell.

159
00:20:12,060 --> 00:20:20,450
A concept is a mental amalgamation of the memory of many perceptions which is cemented by beliefs and culture.

160
00:20:22,211 --> 00:20:34,645
Primitive man, for example, would not have had the concept doorbell, and if he heard one, might have been sorting through his memory of birdsongs to try to recognise this peculiarly shrill one.

161
00:20:36,468 --> 00:20:40,531
Concepts get strung together to form thoughts and mental images.

162
00:20:41,827 --> 00:20:52,122
A pattern of light, shade and colour falls on the eye and the mind recognises our neighbour's face and we think, here's John from down the road.

163
00:20:55,386 --> 00:21:05,480
It's truly amazing how the mind can recognise and classify the complex patterns of sight and smell and sound that it is bombarded with each moment.

164
00:21:07,242 --> 00:21:11,008
But each perception is just a guess at the reality that stimulated it.

165
00:21:11,967 --> 00:21:21,340
like my seeing the red cloth brushing the floor and my mind constructing a life-size image of Bhante Bodhidharma, as I explained in another talk.

166
00:21:24,566 --> 00:21:38,987
So perceptions with their resulting concepts, mental images and thoughts are very, very clever guesswork based on what we remember and what we believe to be likely and some incoming data from the senses.

167
00:21:40,721 --> 00:21:44,327
They impose a structure in the world that we would swear to be true.

168
00:21:44,387 --> 00:21:47,673
And this can certainly be helpful.

169
00:21:48,295 --> 00:21:54,365
For example, we need to recognise a certain pattern of light as a cup in order to drink tea.

170
00:21:56,248 --> 00:22:03,539
Could we accept our perceptions as helpful, clever ways to represent reality, but nothing more than that?

171
00:22:05,208 --> 00:22:12,499
a temporary classification which needs to be continually reconfirmed by checking against our sensory input.

172
00:22:13,881 --> 00:22:20,411
Then we wouldn't get so startled when the cup shatters into little pieces spilling all the tea.

173
00:22:24,517 --> 00:22:33,190
Take for example our deeply held belief that there's someone called me whose location is probably within or nearby my body.

174
00:22:34,334 --> 00:22:38,561
This knee is, or should be, in control of my body and my life.

175
00:22:40,505 --> 00:22:45,173
The Buddha taught that this perception of self is created as part of the reaction to Vedana.

176
00:22:46,255 --> 00:22:58,317
In order to get what it wants, or get rid of what it doesn't want, the mind-body complex lets desire generate a perception of a self that can take decisions and get the body into action.

177
00:22:59,630 --> 00:23:04,796
It's a wonderfully clever way that our biology has found to satisfy its needs.

178
00:23:09,080 --> 00:23:17,111
Despite our deep belief in the reality of me, the Buddha teaches that the real truth is anatta, not self.

179
00:23:19,173 --> 00:23:21,976
This is a very difficult teaching to get our heads around.

180
00:23:23,038 --> 00:23:25,941
But some people have sudden insights into anatta.

181
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:29,963
While walking in the Himalayas, D.E.

182
00:23:30,044 --> 00:23:34,530
Harding experienced a moment in which all his mental chatter died down.

183
00:23:34,570 --> 00:23:40,759
As if I had been born that instant, innocent of all memories.

184
00:23:42,122 --> 00:23:55,101
He looked down to find a pair of trouser legs terminating in a pair of brown shoes, sleeves terminating sideways in a pair of pink hands, and a shirt front terminating in nothing whatsoever.

185
00:23:55,958 --> 00:24:01,363
But this nothing, this hole where his head should have been, was no ordinary vacancy.

186
00:24:02,344 --> 00:24:08,471
The emptiness was filled with mountains, trees and sky, everything in his visual field.

187
00:24:09,612 --> 00:24:12,094
He had lost a head and gained a world.

188
00:24:12,134 --> 00:24:23,586
There arose no questions, he said, but only peace and a quiet joy, and the sensation of having dropped an intolerable burden.

189
00:24:26,214 --> 00:24:33,278
So the perception of anatta is a very beautiful one which can arise quite naturally when the mental chatter dies down.

190
00:24:34,382 --> 00:24:38,115
But the thought of anatta is often unsettling or even frightening.

191
00:24:39,951 --> 00:24:51,190
The Buddha never answered questions of the form, do I exist or is there a self, but asked people to experience for themselves that the perception of self is conditional.

192
00:24:52,112 --> 00:24:56,198
It arises when there is a desire for whatever Vedana is felt.

193
00:24:58,461 --> 00:25:05,452
The sense of self, like all perceptions, is the mind's guess at how to interpret present reality.

194
00:25:07,811 --> 00:25:25,669
When a pattern of black and yellow light strikes the eye and gives rise to the very unpleasant thought of a tiger about to pounce, it makes a lot of sense to get our biological act together using the concept of me being in control and putting all my energy into escaping.

195
00:25:26,864 --> 00:25:37,358
And if the tiger catches us and we see we're doomed, it makes sense to change our minds and see that this painful, frightened entity is not our true self.

196
00:25:37,378 --> 00:25:41,605
In that sublime state, we could even wish the tiger Bon Appetit!

197
00:25:44,048 --> 00:25:51,138
Can we see the self as a temporary, provisional, best guess at interpreting present reality?

198
00:25:52,701 --> 00:25:55,925
Very helpful at times, but not the ultimate truth.

199
00:25:57,442 --> 00:26:01,026
Can we see it wax and wane as circumstances dictate?

200
00:26:02,646 --> 00:26:07,811
For example, the way a sense of me suddenly blossoms when something nice happens.

201
00:26:09,153 --> 00:26:14,318
It's very interesting to note that you didn't remark on its absence before the sudden blossoming.

202
00:26:15,880 --> 00:26:19,624
The experience of not-self is very subtle and unobtrusive.

203
00:26:20,525 --> 00:26:22,487
That's why we don't notice it.

204
00:26:23,529 --> 00:26:28,275
It's quite an unremarkable experience, until we think about it.

205
00:26:29,836 --> 00:26:36,784
The experience of self, on the other hand, always calls attention, even if it's an unpleasant experience.

206
00:26:37,325 --> 00:26:44,353
For example, the way that sense of me crumples or rears up in anger when something unpleasant happens.

207
00:26:47,576 --> 00:26:51,039
Let's look now at the fourth Kanda, Sankara.

208
00:26:52,960 --> 00:26:55,222
There are many translations for Sankara.

209
00:26:56,304 --> 00:27:05,996
Mental formations, mental factors, mental habits, habitual tendencies, even concoctions.

210
00:27:08,019 --> 00:27:15,508
In everyday language we refer to some of these as moods and emotions such as depression, anger, love, joy.

211
00:27:16,770 --> 00:27:26,085
Others, such as laziness, we might think of as a state of mind, while others, such as wisdom, we might think of as a mental attribute.

212
00:27:27,707 --> 00:27:34,857
Each moment the Sankara changes with the circumstances we find ourselves in, but each of us favour different sets.

213
00:27:35,298 --> 00:27:42,930
For example, some of us have a tendency towards anger, others for delusion, others for joy, etc.,

214
00:27:44,782 --> 00:27:49,230
Our characters and personalities are determined by our Sankara.

215
00:27:53,900 --> 00:27:57,707
Some Sankara are unwholesome in the sense that they lead to suffering.

216
00:27:59,269 --> 00:28:03,196
Others lead towards Nirvana, termed Beautiful Sankara.

217
00:28:05,134 --> 00:28:07,017
Others are ethically neutral.

218
00:28:07,076 --> 00:28:11,143
They can be present in either wholesome or unwholesome states.

219
00:28:12,364 --> 00:28:21,375
One of the neutral Sankara is volition, which is particularly important because it links with karma, the ethical force at work in life.

220
00:28:24,138 --> 00:28:31,048
Volition, also translated as intention or will, factors into every conscious moment.

221
00:28:32,368 --> 00:28:34,652
Even seeing and hearing are intentional.

222
00:28:35,644 --> 00:28:38,949
So every moment we are sowing Kama for ourselves.

223
00:28:40,790 --> 00:28:42,413
Kama is like a seed.

224
00:28:43,413 --> 00:28:44,736
It ripens as fruit .

225
00:28:45,876 --> 00:28:54,949
Actions or speech motivated by kindness or other beautiful qualities ripen as various forms of happiness.

226
00:28:56,711 --> 00:29:02,698
Actions motivated by hatred or other unwholesome qualities ripen as unhappiness.

227
00:29:04,450 --> 00:29:11,400
Kama ripens in many ways, but perhaps the most important is the type of sankara they develop.

228
00:29:13,262 --> 00:29:22,056
If we're motivated by greed to steal someone's wallet, we develop habits of greed, deceitfulness, shamelessness, among others.

229
00:29:23,838 --> 00:29:30,828
If we're motivated by kindness to care for a sick child, we develop habits such as patience, compassion, love.

230
00:29:32,429 --> 00:29:36,555
It is the motivation that matters, not the act itself.

231
00:29:39,077 --> 00:29:51,954
If we care for the child because we feel trapped into this role and we let resentment be shown and make cruel remarks now and then, then we develop cruelty and resentment rather than beautiful Sankara.

232
00:29:55,319 --> 00:30:00,006
Non-attachment and non-hatred are amongst the beautiful Sankara.

233
00:30:01,893 --> 00:30:09,300
These are very unexciting terms, but I had a striking demonstration of the beauty of non-attachment during one retreat.

234
00:30:11,303 --> 00:30:16,328
There was a bed of wild flowers in the garden, and I was enthralled by the gorgeous colours.

235
00:30:17,509 --> 00:30:31,005
But my mind would get lost in thoughts of sowing a flower bed like this at home, and my friends would surely want one too, and on and on it went until I was tense with anxiety about these future gardens.

236
00:30:32,538 --> 00:30:37,261
Although the scene in front of me was beautiful, I felt contorted by tension.

237
00:30:38,663 --> 00:30:44,690
I sadly decided I would have to forgo the gorgeous flower bed if I was to get any peace of mind.

238
00:30:46,750 --> 00:30:58,883
Then one day as I was drying dishes, there was a moment where I simply felt the weight of the cup and the softness of the cloth, and my mind expanded into a beautiful freedom.

239
00:31:00,179 --> 00:31:05,963
It was a moment without attachment, but one of the most beautiful experiences of my life.

240
00:31:08,366 --> 00:31:14,452
I had never realised how much I was clinging until I experienced that one moment of non-attachment.

241
00:31:16,153 --> 00:31:26,523
Comparing this with my experience at the flowerbed, I could see that attachment leads to misery, while non-attachment allows perfect contentment.

242
00:31:29,238 --> 00:31:38,986
Non-hatred also sounds mundane but can be put in more positive language as friendliness, kindness, love and patience.

243
00:31:40,207 --> 00:31:47,292
As you would expect, compassion, equanimity and sympathetic joy are also among the beautiful states of mind.

244
00:31:50,715 --> 00:31:58,823
We cling to this candour by identifying ourselves with our emotions and mind states thinking I am angry, I am happy

245
00:31:59,511 --> 00:32:00,452
I am sleepy.

246
00:32:02,154 --> 00:32:11,443
The truth of the matter is that these are temporary states of mind which arise because of certain conditions and cease when these conditions pass away.

247
00:32:13,945 --> 00:32:20,813
When we get closely identified with any mind state we become blind to any alternative way of viewing the situation.

248
00:32:21,913 --> 00:32:24,557
So the mind loses its flexibility

249
00:32:26,038 --> 00:32:30,846
During a long car journey I was feeling a bit sick and very grumpy.

250
00:32:32,229 --> 00:32:34,271
A friend smiled and made some pleasantry.

251
00:32:35,354 --> 00:32:44,367
For a moment I forgot to be grumpy and my heart lifted but then I remembered I am grumpy and started sinking back into the state.

252
00:32:45,890 --> 00:32:52,299
But the momentary lift showed me the state wasn't the absolute truth and I could make the effort to be sociable.

253
00:32:53,478 --> 00:32:59,250
I found myself resisting, feeling who would be disloyal to my grumpy self, who deserved my loyalty.

254
00:32:59,269 --> 00:33:09,951
On digesting this, my sociability related Sankara's one out over my self-loyalty ones, and I decided to perk up a bit.

255
00:33:13,086 --> 00:33:17,153
As always, mindfulness is the key to seeing through delusion.

256
00:33:17,894 --> 00:33:26,926
In this case, the belief that I am grumpy, rather than a more accurate belief such as grumpiness is here now, but conditions could change.

257
00:33:28,890 --> 00:33:38,924
It's also easy to cling to Sankara like love, joy, compassion, understanding, not seeing how these come and go depending on circumstances.

258
00:33:40,271 --> 00:33:46,519
When we've had a good meal or heard some good news, we can feel kind, happy and understanding.

259
00:33:47,980 --> 00:33:51,825
It's so, so tempting to believe this is the real me.

260
00:33:52,905 --> 00:33:56,990
But then there is shock and grief when this wonderful state gets broken down again.

261
00:33:58,772 --> 00:34:07,343
Can we notice the beautiful Sankara objectively, enjoying them while they last, letting them go when the conditions change?

262
00:34:08,992 --> 00:34:10,275
It's a tough practice.

263
00:34:11,637 --> 00:34:15,523
We have to let everything go for the sake of complete freedom.

264
00:34:21,632 --> 00:34:25,438
This brings us to the last of the canda, consciousness.

265
00:34:27,561 --> 00:34:34,873
To be conscious is to experience the other four canda, the sensory world around us and the mental world within.

266
00:34:36,315 --> 00:34:37,617
If we are unconscious,

267
00:34:38,152 --> 00:34:39,675
this experience vanishes.

268
00:34:41,197 --> 00:34:47,565
This is the sense in which the term consciousness is used when it refers to the fifth khanda.

269
00:34:52,612 --> 00:34:59,501
Consciousness can also be used to refer to the experience of nibbana but that's not included in the khanda.

270
00:35:00,342 --> 00:35:03,485
The khanda only describe what we cling to.

271
00:35:03,583 --> 00:35:08,648
and nibbana is what we're left with when we stop clinging to the canda.

272
00:35:11,572 --> 00:35:16,016
Consciousness is often likened to a screen on which a film project.

273
00:35:17,097 --> 00:35:22,403
The light from the projector has to fall on the screen if we are to see the scenery and characters.

274
00:35:23,465 --> 00:35:32,594
If there was no screen, the light would just pass through and if there were no dust in the air to scatter it, the light beam would be invisible.

275
00:35:32,896 --> 00:35:34,557
it would make no impact on us.

276
00:35:36,340 --> 00:35:53,978
In the same way the various dramas of our lives as well as their component parts of sights, sounds, smells, tastes, body sensations and mental activity all have to project onto the screen of consciousness to have any impact on us.

277
00:35:57,523 --> 00:36:02,547
Is there a difference between consciousness, awareness and mindfulness?

278
00:36:04,806 --> 00:36:09,811
Sometimes the words are used interchangeably, so it can be confusing.

279
00:36:11,193 --> 00:36:15,295
For this talk, I use awareness and mindfulness interchangeably.

280
00:36:17,217 --> 00:36:19,940
We all know that we can be conscious though not mindful.

281
00:36:20,900 --> 00:36:30,590
We are on autopilot, letting the mind run away on thoughts but not noticing that these thoughts are just part of our present experience.

282
00:36:30,610 --> 00:36:32,771
Going back to the movie analogy,

283
00:36:33,240 --> 00:36:40,255
It's as if we're in the movie, playing our role, feeling our feelings, totally immersed in the plot.

284
00:36:42,338 --> 00:36:49,833
Mindfulness turns attention to our conscious experience and the mind starts taking an interest in what's being projected on the screen.

285
00:36:51,436 --> 00:36:54,844
It's often described as a different level of consciousness.

286
00:36:56,039 --> 00:37:03,590
We can have stretches where we see the film quite objectively, like watching ourselves acting in the movie of our lives.

287
00:37:04,971 --> 00:37:12,322
Then we lose mindfulness and get sucked into some aspect of the plot that was on the screen, acting it all out with gusto.

288
00:37:13,103 --> 00:37:24,679
The Buddha taught that there are six separate doorways to consciousness, involving the five senses and also the mind, for example, when a thought or memory falls on the screen of consciousness.

289
00:37:26,514 --> 00:37:29,699
Certain conditions have to be fulfilled for each door to open.

290
00:37:31,161 --> 00:37:38,012
In order to hear a bird song, for example, we need the bird to sing, good hearing, as well as attention.

291
00:37:39,514 --> 00:37:43,480
If any of these is missing, then hearing consciousness does not happen.

292
00:37:45,222 --> 00:37:51,992
Although we say, isn't the silence beautiful, we can't actually hear silence.

293
00:37:52,012 --> 00:37:55,677
Perhaps what we're enjoying is the absence of hearing consciousness.

294
00:37:57,733 --> 00:37:59,835
It's the same for all the other senses.

295
00:38:00,858 --> 00:38:05,782
We need the sense object, sensory physiology and attention.

296
00:38:09,668 --> 00:38:16,615
Sight, sound, body sensations, smell, taste and mental activities.

297
00:38:17,757 --> 00:38:21,681
All of these are separate doorways to conscious experience.

298
00:38:23,483 --> 00:38:27,588
But they are completely separate independent experiences.

299
00:38:29,965 --> 00:38:35,791
I first noticed this separation of the different fields of consciousness one time while walking during a retreat.

300
00:38:35,811 --> 00:38:41,697
I was noting the feeling of the feet swinging forward and stepping down onto the ground.

301
00:38:43,498 --> 00:38:45,822
So my attention was on body consciousness.

302
00:38:47,503 --> 00:38:54,471
But then I suddenly saw the tip of my foot appearing and disappearing as I felt it come to the end of the forward swing.

303
00:38:55,750 --> 00:39:00,454
I found myself being amazed that these experiences coincided so perfectly.

304
00:39:01,976 --> 00:39:06,922
Before that, I would never have questioned that the sight and feel of the foot would coincide.

305
00:39:08,503 --> 00:39:16,152
But now I could sense that logical expectations, sight and bodily sensations were occupying three separate worlds.

306
00:39:17,634 --> 00:39:24,541
It seemed a pure wonder and an incredible gift that they all fitted into each other so neatly.

307
00:39:26,782 --> 00:39:30,949
I was tasting the separation of consciousness into its six fields.

308
00:39:33,952 --> 00:39:45,550
See can you tune into the different fields of consciousness, for example vision, hearing and bodily experience.

309
00:39:45,570 --> 00:39:49,416
Joseph Goldstein recommends using noting phrases of the form

310
00:39:50,105 --> 00:39:54,713
Sounds being known, walking being known, etc.

311
00:39:55,153 --> 00:39:58,940
to turn attention towards that entity which registers experience.

312
00:40:00,523 --> 00:40:06,813
Can you get a sense of how separate are the worlds of hearing, seeing and physical sensing?

313
00:40:09,679 --> 00:40:20,552
The Buddha also taught that we only experience one doorway for consciousness at a time sight or sound or smell or mental activity etc.

314
00:40:21,793 --> 00:40:27,099
But this is all happening at such a fast rate that we don't notice the separate registrations.

315
00:40:29,543 --> 00:40:35,010
Once I was walking towards a door to open it feeling the feet lifting, moving etc.

316
00:40:36,510 --> 00:40:39,534
Then my hand went out to grasp the handle of the door

317
00:40:40,190 --> 00:40:59,076
touching turning turning pushing pushing then my foot lifted to take another step at the moment i felt the foot lift i realized my hand had disappeared totally from consciousness

318
00:40:59,427 --> 00:41:03,052
I got such a fright I looked down to see if my hand had dropped off.

319
00:41:04,034 --> 00:41:13,748
But it was still there and I realised it was simply that perception had sharpened so that I was experiencing just one sensation at a time.

320
00:41:17,514 --> 00:41:27,949
These kinds of experience undermine our usual fascination with the plot that's playing on the screen of consciousness and make us wonder about the nature of consciousness itself.

321
00:41:30,240 --> 00:41:41,313
To study this fifth canda, we need to calm ourselves in meditation sufficiently to extract ourselves from the fascination of the plot and simply watch the film.

322
00:41:43,454 --> 00:41:56,889
Then at times we might relax enough to get a sense of what often feels like a more stable sense of self, the one who watches the film, the one who knows experience, the observer, the witness.

323
00:41:57,594 --> 00:42:02,061
At those moments we're noticing our identification with the fifth khanda.

324
00:42:03,284 --> 00:42:09,632
We sense this is happening within me or I am observing all this.

325
00:42:13,918 --> 00:42:17,684
Bhante uses the analogy of looking through a shop window.

326
00:42:19,067 --> 00:42:24,936
You see the goods inside but might also notice your own reflection as you watch.

327
00:42:26,317 --> 00:42:31,226
If the stuff for sale doesn't appeal, you might get more interested in your own face.

328
00:42:32,849 --> 00:42:46,097
In the same way, when our consciousness film is not too exciting, we can bring attention to the sense of me, the one who experiences, observes and knows all this.

329
00:42:48,456 --> 00:42:57,530
Although at first it feels like a deep and reliable sense of self, it also begins to shift and slide when the spotlight turns upon it.

330
00:42:59,652 --> 00:43:05,221
So we begin to lose faith in this final candour as a stable source of happiness.

331
00:43:08,865 --> 00:43:13,311
At other times we lose that sense of watching the screen but remain mindful.

332
00:43:14,693 --> 00:43:18,378
We feel more intimate with sensations and feelings.

333
00:43:18,916 --> 00:43:22,800
They're no longer out there on the screen for me to watch.

334
00:43:24,382 --> 00:43:27,005
This is the loss of identity with the fifth canda.

335
00:43:28,487 --> 00:43:35,036
Sensations and feelings arise and pass just as before, but no one is watching anymore.

336
00:43:36,538 --> 00:43:38,219
It's an experience of anatta.

337
00:43:39,842 --> 00:43:46,289
Our whole system functions just fine without the usual sense of me being in charge or watching the film.

338
00:43:47,806 --> 00:43:56,719
In our earlier analogy, we're now tasting freefall, no longer clinging even to this fifth khanda for security.

339
00:43:58,501 --> 00:44:07,315
Each sensation of life is intimately known, but there's no central control system, no observer, no unknowing.

340
00:44:09,157 --> 00:44:14,286
We glimpse the state of non-clinging, the end of suffering, nibbana.

341
00:44:16,088 --> 00:44:29,684
However, until our trust in this state deepens to total enlightenment, the sense of self sooner or later rears its head again as we start clinging to familiar experiences to help us feel secure.

342
00:44:36,172 --> 00:44:42,940
Studying the Kanda helps us to discover what it is we cling to unwittingly creating dukkha in the process.

343
00:44:44,302 --> 00:44:51,215
Ultimately, all our clinging boils down to wanting to feel good, clinging to pleasant vedana.

344
00:44:53,619 --> 00:45:06,143
In an effort to do this, we scrabble around in the heap of material form, buying goods, nice clothes, makeup, in an effort to feel secure about our bodies and our material well-being.

345
00:45:07,961 --> 00:45:15,221
Or else we polish our spectacles, choose a new pair of lenses as we immerse ourselves in the heap of perceptions.

346
00:45:17,686 --> 00:45:24,704
At other times we get lost in the heap of Sankara, repeating old habits in an effort to get things stable.

347
00:45:26,422 --> 00:45:37,836
When we're relaxed and mindful, we fall into the heap of consciousness, concocting stability from the illusion that there's someone called me who experiences my life.

348
00:45:41,260 --> 00:45:55,418
The good news is that deeper awareness of our habit of clinging and how much it hurts makes us more willing to let go and free fall with the truths of Anicca, Dukkha, Anatta.

349
00:45:57,052 --> 00:46:00,677
we get more curious about the state of non-clinging.

350
00:46:02,719 --> 00:46:11,753
Instead of the temporary highs offered by the Kanda, we become enthralled by the possibility of letting these slip through our fingers.

351
00:46:13,715 --> 00:46:19,684
We discover the stability offered by knowing the instability of life.

352
00:46:22,313 --> 00:46:29,117
May these reflections on the five khanda help us experience the joy of non-clinging.

